 the implications of their extraction are global. Klinger excavates the rich historical origins and ongoing ramifications of the quest to mine rare earths in ever more impossible places.Klinger writes about the devastating damage to lives and the environment caused by the exploitation of rare earths. She demonstrates in human terms how scarcity myths have been conscripted into diverse geopolitical campaigns that use rare earth mining as a pretext to capture spaces that have historically fallen beyond the grasp of centralized power. These include legally and logistically forbidding locations in the Amazon, Greenland, and Afghanistan, and on the Moon.  afunded by Knowledge Unlatched  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aLunar mining. 0aRare earth metalsxPolitical aspects. 0aRare earth metalsxSocial aspects. 0aRare earth metalszBrazilzAmazonas. 0aRare earth metalszChinazInner Mongolia. 4aGeography-Physical & Cultural. 4aHistory Of Technology. 4aPolitical Science & Political History.  abooks about living on the moon.  acerium.  adiscovery of rare earth metals.  aearth science.  aeconomic conditions.  aenergy studies.  aexploitation of rare earths.  aextractive industries.  ageographic science.  ageopolitics.  ageostrategic consequences of rare earth metals.  ahuman geography.  aimpact of rare earth metals.  alanthanum.  alunar mining.  amineral composition.  amineral properties.  amineral resources.  amining business.  amining on the moon.  amining science.  amining technology.  amining.  apolitical economy of rare earth metals.  apolitical economy.  apower resources.  arare earth elements.  arare earth metal extraction.  arare earth metals in brazil.  arare earth metals in china.  arare earth metals in inner mongolia.  arare earth metals.  ar